docs.lead_paragraph: The White House and Democratic Congressional leaders, scrambling for a backup plan to rescue their health care legislation if Republicans win the special election in Massachusetts on Tuesday, have begun laying the groundwork to ask House Democrats to approve the Senate version of the bill and send it directly to President Obama for his signature. A victory by the Republican, Scott Brown, in Massachusetts would deny Democrats the 60th vote they need in the Senate to surmount Republican filibusters and advance the health legislation.

headline.main: democrats seek options to keep health bill alive

docs.abstract: White House and Democratic Congressional leaders scramble for backup plan to rescue health care legislation if Republicans win special election in Massachusetts; begin laying groundwork to ask House Democrats to approve Senate version of bill and send it directly to Pres Obama for his signature; victory by Republican Scott Brown in Massachusetts would deny Democrats 60th Senate vote they need to surmount filibuster and advance bill; while some Democrats suggest asking House Democrats to speed bill to Obama's desk even if their candidate Martha Coakley wins narrow victory, it is unclear if rank-and-file Democrats will go along; House Speaker Nancy Pelosi affirms legislation will move forward regardless of outcome of special election; still, House Democrats voice number of complaints with Senate measure and White House officials and Congressional leaders have struggled to bridge differences between two bills (L)
